}\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!align=\"left\" style=\"width: 17em\"|TEAM\n|-bgcolor=gold\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 1.png]]\n|{{wpw|RUS}} \n|-bgcolor=silver\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 2.png]]\n|{{wpw|ITA}}\n|-bgcolor=cc9966\n|align=\"center\"|[[Image:Med 3.png]]\n|{{wpw|HUN}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|4.\n|{{wpw|ESP}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|5.\n|{{wpw|NED}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|6.\n|{{wpw|GRE}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|7.\n|{{wpw|GER}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|8.\n|{{wpw|SRB}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n{{winners|wpw|2006 Women's European Champion|RUS|First}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Individual awards==\n*'''Most Valuable Player'''\n**{{flagathlete|[[Tania di Mario]]|ITA}}\n*'''Best Goalkeeper'''\n**{{flagathlete|[[Elena Gigli]]|ITA}}\n*'''Topscorer'''\n**{{flagathlete|[[Ekaterina Pantolina]]|RUS}} &mdash; 18 goals\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.lenweb.org/competitions/Belgrade_2006/index.php?pag=PROGRAMME_WOMEN LEN Results]\n<br>\n{{European Water Polo Championship}}\n<br>\n\n[[Category:Women's European Water Polo Championship|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 in women's water polo|E]]\n[[Category:2006 in Serbian women's sport|W]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Zagreb|W]]\n[[Category:International water polo competitions hosted by Serbia]]\n[[Category:2006 European Water Polo Championship|Women's]]\n[[Category:2000s in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:September 2006 sports events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_Women%27s_European_Water_Polo_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Jay Schellen", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                  = Jay Schellen\n| image                 = Jay pic.jpg\n| caption               =\n| background            = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name            = Jay Schellen\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1960|05|20}}\n| birth_place           = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n| alias                 =\n| occupation            = Musician\n| instrument            = [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n| genre                 = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[Progressive rock]], [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active          = 1979-present\n| associated_acts       = [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]<br>[[Asia (band)|Asia]]<br>[[Circa (band)|Circa]]<br>[[World Trade (band)|World Trade]]<br>[[Unruly Child]]<br>[[Asia Featuring John Payne]]<br>Sircle of Silence<br>Stone Fury<br>[[GPS (band)|GPS]]<br>[[Yes (band)|Yes]]\n}}\n\n'''Jay Schellen''' (born May 20, 1960) is an American drummer who is best known as a member of the hard rock band [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]. Schellen has also worked and currently working with a number of other heavy rock and [[progressive rock]] bands, including with [[Asia (band)|Asia]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Moon |first=Jill |title=Touring Asia: Longtime frontman John Payne brings own band version |url=http://www.thetelegraph.com/articles/version-40106-john-alton.html |accessdate=January 25, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Alton)|The Telegraph]] |date=May 12, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723072449/http://www.thetelegraph.com/articles/version-40106-john-alton.html |archivedate=July 23, 2011 }}</ref> [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]], [[Circa (band)|Circa]], [[Unruly Child]], and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1979 as a teen  Jay was introduced to the big Stage touring with R&B Legend [[Al Wilson]] (\"Show and Tell\") supporting [[The Ohio Players]].  After moving to Los Angeles in 1981 Jay broke into the LA session scene and played local stages with former Yes guitarist [[Peter Banks]]' band and National arenas with Danny Johnson and The Bandits supporting [[ZZ Top]]. In 1982, Schellen was invited to join English pop band [[Badfinger]] joining Tommy Evans, Joey Molland, Glen Sherba and Yes keyboardist [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]].\n\nIn 1984, Schellen joined Stone Fury, working with singer [[Lenny Wolf]] and guitarist [[Bruce Gowdy]]. From 1985 to 1991, he joined the [[melodic rock]] group [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]. Hurricane went on to record three records, ''Take What You Want'', ''Over the Edge'' and ''Slave to the Thrill'', 3 worldwide tours and posted two top ten [[MTV]] videos. In 1993, Schellen joined Gowdy in a new [[melodic rock]] project, [[Unruly Child]], releasing a self-titled CD. Schellen again worked with Gowdy in 1995, joining [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] for their second album ''Euphoria'', alongside [[Billy Sherwood]] (later in Yes). Schellen and Sherwood were the only members of World Trade for appearances on two tribute albums released on the [[Magna Carta]] record label in 1995.\n\nIn 1995\u20131997, Schellen formed Sircle of Silence with singer [[David Reece]] (ex-[[Accept (band)|Accept]], ex-[[Bangalore Choir]]), guitarist Larry Farkas (ex-[[Vengeance Rising]], ex-[[Die Happy (band)|Die Happy]]) and bass guitarist [[Greg Chaisson]] (ex-[[Badlands (American band)|Badlands]]). In 1997, Schellen published his well regarded drum method book Rocking Independence. In 1998, he played in ''Heaven and Earth'' with former Hurricane bandmate [[Kelly Hansen]] and guitarist [[Stuart Saunders Smith]]. 1998-1999 saw a second Unruly Child album with Gowdy and Hansen. In 1999, Schellen played on Sherwood's debut solo album ''The Big Peace'', while the next year he recorded for Sherwood's project with Yes bassist [[Chris Squire]], ''[[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]]''. In 2003, Schellen re-joined Conspiracy, recording ''The Unknown'', followed by a live-in-the-studio DVD recorded in 2004 and released in 2006. Schellen has continued to work with Sherwood on a number of other projects including joining progressive group [[Circa (band)|Circa]] in 2008 (replacing [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]]), thus re-joining [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] again on keyboards and [[Jimmy Haun]] on guitars. They released ''Circa HQ'' in January 2009. He also worked with [[Yoso]] in the band's initial stages, again working with Sherwood and Kaye. In 2010 Jay joined Sherwood,  Jimmy Haun and Kaye again to perform \"Headsets\" in collaboration with legendary Rock and Roll DJ  [[Jim Ladd]] staged at the [[Laserium]] in Los Angeles, California.\n\nIn 2004, Schellen with Sherwood worked on pre-production for [[Asia (band)|Asia]]'s album ''Silent Nation'' with [[Geoff Downes]] (another former Yes keyboardist). In August 2005, Schellen replaced [[Chris Slade]] as the drummer in [[Asia (band)|Asia]]. The group toured Europe extensively and released a live recording, however, in 2006, Downes left the line up for a reunion of the original founding members Asia quartet: Schellen and the other two Asia band members, singer [[John Payne (singer)|John Payne]] and guitarist [[Guthrie Govan]], formed a new band, [[GPS (band)|GPS]]. GPS released their debut CD ''Window to the Soul''. In 2008, [[Asia Featuring John Payne]] was formed with Payne, Govan, keyboardist [[Erik Norlander]], and Schellen on drums. An album was released under the new name of Dukes of the Orient. Unruly Child has also reunited.\n\nFrom September 2013, he was performing in the Las Vegas production of ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]'', initially alongside his Asia bandmate John Payne.\n\nIn 2016, Schellen temporarily replaced Yes drummer [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] on their 2016 North American tour while White recovered from back surgery and continued to play with them alongside White through White's recovery until February 2017. For the February 2018 Cruise to the Edge shows, Schellen once again performed as second guest drummer to support White, who has been battling a bacterial infection in his joints since November 2017.\n\nSchellen plays dw drums, Remo drumheads, and Zildjian cymbals and sticks.\n\n==Discography==\n*Hurricane - ''Take What You Want''\n*Hurricane - ''Over the Edge''\n*Hurricane - ''[[Slave to the Thrill]]''\n*[[Unruly Child]] - ''Unruly Child''\n*[[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] - ''Euphoria''\n*[[Billy Sherwood]] - ''The Big Peace'' (1999)\n*[[Chris Squire]] & Billy Sherwood - ''Conspiracy''\n*[[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]] - ''The Unknown''\n*[[Yes (band)|Yes]] - ''[[Topographic Drama \u2013 Live Across America]]'' (2017)\n*[[Peter Banks]] - ''[[Be Well, Be Safe, Be Lucky... The Anthology]]'' (2018)\n*[[Dukes of the Orient]] - ''Dukes of the Orient'' (2018)\n*[[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and [[Peter Banks]] - ''[[Crossover (David Cross and Peter Banks album)|Crossover]]'' (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jayschellen.com/ JaySchellen.com] \u2013 official website\n\n{{Asiaband}}\n{{Hurricane (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schellen, Jay}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Asia (band) members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Circa (band) members]]\n[[Category:Yoso members]]\n[[Category:Hurricane (band) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                  = Jay Schellen\n| image                 = Jay pic.jpg\n| caption               =\n| background            = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name            = Jay Schellen\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1960|05|20}}\n| birth_place           = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n| alias                 =\n| occupation            = Musician\n| instrument            = [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n| genre                 = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[Progressive rock]], [[Hard rock]]\n| years_active          = 1979-present\n| associated_acts       = [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]<br>[[Asia (band)|Asia]]<br>[[Circa (band)|Circa]]<br>[[World Trade (band)|World Trade]]<br>[[Unruly Child]]<br>[[Asia Featuring John Payne]]<br>Sircle of Silence<br>Stone Fury<br>[[GPS (band)|GPS]]<br>[[Yes (band)|Yes]]\n}}\n\n'''Jay Schellen''' (born May 20, 1960) is an American drummer who is best known as a member of the hard rock band [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]. Schellen has also worked and currently working with a number of other heavy rock and [[progressive rock]] bands, including with [[Asia (band)|Asia]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Moon |first=Jill |title=Touring Asia: Longtime frontman John Payne brings own band version |url=http://www.thetelegraph.com/articles/version-40106-john-alton.html |accessdate=January 25, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Alton)|The Telegraph]] |date=May 12, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723072449/http://www.thetelegraph.com/articles/version-40106-john-alton.html |archivedate=July 23, 2011 }}</ref> [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]], [[Circa (band)|Circa]], [[Unruly Child]], and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1979 as a teen  Jay was introduced to the big Stage touring with R&B Legend [[Al Wilson]] (\"Show and Tell\") supporting [[The Ohio Players]].  After moving to Los Angeles in 1981 Jay broke into the LA session scene and played local stages with former Yes guitarist [[Peter Banks]]' band and National arenas with Danny Johnson and The Bandits supporting [[ZZ Top]]. In 1982, Schellen was invited to join English pop band [[Badfinger]] joining Tommy Evans, Joey Molland, Glen Sherba and Yes keyboardist [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]].\n\nIn 1984, Schellen joined Stone Fury, working with singer [[Lenny Wolf]] and guitarist [[Bruce Gowdy]]. From 1985 to 1991, he joined the [[melodic rock]] group [[Hurricane (American band)|Hurricane]]. Hurricane went on to record three records, ''Take What You Want'', ''Over the Edge'' and ''Slave to the Thrill'', 3 world wide tours and posted two top ten [[MTV]] videos. In 1993, Schellen joined Gowdy in a new [[melodic rock]] project, [[Unruly Child]], releasing a self-titled CD. Schellen again worked with Gowdy in 1995, joining [[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] for their second album ''Euphoria'', alongside [[Billy Sherwood]] (later in Yes). Schellen and Sherwood were the only members of World Trade for appearances on two tribute albums released on the [[Magna Carta]] record label in 1995.\n\nIn 1995-1997, Schellen formed Sircle of Silence with singer [[David Reece]] (ex-[[Accept (band)|Accept]], ex-[[Bangalore Choir]]), guitarist Larry Farkas (ex-[[Vengeance Rising]], ex-[[Die Happy (band)|Die Happy]]) and bass guitarist [[Greg Chaisson]] (ex-[[Badlands (American band)|Badlands]]). In 1997, Schellen published his well regarded drum method book Rocking Independence. In 1998, he played in ''Heaven and Earth'' with former Hurricane bandmate [[Kelly Hansen]] and guitarist [[Stuart Saunders Smith]]. 1998-1999 saw a second Unruly Child album with Gowdy and Hansen. In 1999, Schellen played on Sherwood's debut solo album ''The Big Peace'', while the next year he recorded for Sherwood's project with Yes bassist [[Chris Squire]], ''[[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]]''. In 2003, Schellen re-joined Conspiracy, recording ''The Unknown'', followed by a live-in-the-studio DVD recorded in 2004 and released in 2006. Schellen has continued to work with Sherwood on a number of other projects including joining progressive group [[Circa (band)|Circa]] in 2008 (replacing [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]]), thus re-joining [[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] again on keyboards and [[Jimmy Haun]] on guitars. They released ''Circa HQ'' in January 2009. He also worked with [[Yoso]] in the band's initial stages, again working with Sherwood and Kaye. In 2010 Jay joined Sherwood,  Jimmy Haun and Kaye again to perform \"Headsets\" in collaboration with legendary Rock and Roll DJ  [[Jim Ladd]] staged at the [[Laserium]] in Los Angeles, California.\n\nIn 2004, Schellen with Sherwood worked on pre-production for [[Asia (band)|Asia]]'s album ''Silent Nation'' with [[Geoff Downes]] (another former Yes keyboardist). In August 2005, Schellen replaced [[Chris Slade]] as the drummer in [[Asia (band)|Asia]]. The group toured Europe extensively and released a live recording, however, in 2006, Downes left the line up for a reunion of the original founding members Asia quartet: Schellen and the other two Asia band members, singer [[John Payne (singer)|John Payne]] and guitarist [[Guthrie Govan]], formed a new band, [[GPS (band)|GPS]]. GPS released their debut CD ''Window to the Soul''. In 2008, [[Asia Featuring John Payne]] was formed with Payne, Govan, keyboardist [[Erik Norlander]], and Schellen on drums. An album was released under the new name of Dukes of the Orient. Unruly Child has also reunited.\n\nFrom September 2013, he was performing in the Las Vegas production of ''[[Raiding the Rock Vault]]'', initially alongside his Asia band mate John Payne.\n\nIn 2016, Schellen temporarily replaced Yes drummer [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]] on their 2016 North American tour while White recovered from back surgery and continued to play with them alongside White through White's recovery until February 2017. For the February 2018 Cruise to the Edge shows, Schellen once again performed as second guest drummer to support White, who has been battling a bacterial infection in his joints since November 2017.\n\nSchellen plays dw drums, Remo drumheads, and Zildjian cymbals and sticks.\n\n==Discography==\n*Hurricane - ''Take What You Want''\n*Hurricane - ''Over the Edge''\n*Hurricane - ''[[Slave to the Thrill]]''\n*[[Unruly Child]] - ''Unruly Child''\n*[[World Trade (band)|World Trade]] - ''Euphoria''\n*[[Billy Sherwood]] - ''The Big Peace'' (1999)\n*[[Chris Squire]] & Billy Sherwood - ''Conspiracy''\n*[[Conspiracy (band)|Conspiracy]] - ''The Unknown''\n*[[Yes (band)|Yes]] - ''[[Topographic Drama \u2013 Live Across America]]'' (2017)\n*[[Peter Banks]] - ''[[Be Well, Be Safe, Be Lucky... The Anthology]]'' (2018)\n*[[Dukes of the Orient]] - ''Dukes of the Orient'' (2018)\n*[[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and [[Peter Banks]] - ''[[Crossover (David Cross and Peter Banks album)|Crossover]]'' (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jayschellen.com/ JaySchellen.com] \u2013 official website\n\n{{Asiaband}}\n{{Hurricane (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schellen, Jay}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Asia (band) members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Circa (band) members]]\n[[Category:Yoso members]]\n[[Category:Hurricane (band) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:-,typo(s) fixed: band mate \u2192 bandmate, world wide \u2192 worldwide, 1995-1997 \u2192 1995\u20131997", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Schellen"}
{"title_page": "Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck", "text_new": "{{short description|Ancient Hittite site in northern Turkey}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n  |name = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck\n  |native_name = \n  |alternate_name = \n  |image = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 01.jpg\n  |alt = \n  |caption = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck\n  |map_type = Turkey\n  |map_alt = \n  |map_size= \n  |coordinates = {{coord|40|14|04|N|34|41|44|E|display=inline,title}}\n  |location = [[\u00c7orum Province]], [[Turkey]]\n  |region = [[Anatolia]]\n  |type = Settlement\n  |part_of = \n  |length = \n  |width = \n  |area = \n  |height = \n  |builder = \n  |material = \n  |built = \n  |abandoned = \n  |epochs = \n  |cultures = \n  |dependency_of = \n  |occupants = \n  |event = \n  |excavations = \n  |archaeologists = \n  |condition = In ruins\n  |ownership = \n  |management = \n  |public_access = \n  |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n  |notes = \n}}\n\n'''Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck''' or '''Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck''' (sometimes also spelled as ''Alacah\u00fcy\u00fck'', ''Aladja-Hoyuk'', ''Euyuk'', or ''Evuk'') is the site of a [[Neolithic Age|Neolithic]] and [[Hittites|Hittite]] settlement and is an important [[archaeological site]]. It is situated in [[Alaca]], [[\u00c7orum Province]], [[Turkey]], northeast of [[Bo\u011fazkale]] (formerly and more familiarly [[Bo\u011fazk\u00f6y]]), where the ancient capital city [[Hattusa]] of the [[Hittite Empire]] was situated. Its Hittite name is unknown: connections with [[Arinna]], Tawiniya, and [[Zippalanda]] have all been suggested.<ref>Gorny, Ronald L. \"Zippalanda and Ankuwa: The Geography of Central Anatolia in the Second Millennium B. C.\" ''Journal of the American Oriental Society''. Vol. 117, no. 3, pp. 549-557 (1997).</ref>\n<ref>Popko, Maciej. \"Zippalanda and Ankuwa Once More.\" ''Journal of the American Oriental Society.'' Vol. 120, no. 3, pp. 445-448 (2000).</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sphinx Gate, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 02.jpg|thumb|The Sphinx Gate]]\n\nThe mound ([[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''[[h\u00f6y\u00fck]]'') at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck was a scene of settlement in a continuous sequence of development from the [[Chalcolithic]] Age, when earliest copper tools appeared alongside the use of stone tools.\n\n===Bronze Age===\nDuring the [[Bronze Age|Early Bronze Age]], the mound was the center of a flourishing [[Hattians|Hattian]] culture. It has been continuously occupied ever since, until today's modern settlement in the form of a small village. The standing and distinguishing remains at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, however, such as the \"Sphinx Gate\", date from the [[Hittites|Hittite]] period that followed the Hatti, from the fourteenth century BC.\n\n[[FIle:Royal tomb, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 02.jpg|thumb|A royal tomb in Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck]]\n\nThirteen [[shaft grave|shaft-grave]] \"Royal Tombs\" (EBII, c. 2350\u20132150 BC) in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck contained the dead in [[fetal position]] facing south. They were richly adorned with gold [[fibula]]e, diadems, and belt buckles and repouss\u00e9 gold-leaf figures.\n\nAccording to [[Trevor Bryce]]:\n<blockquote>\n\u2033There is a theory that the occupants of the tombs were not from the native Hattian population of central Anatolia, but were [[Kurgan hypothesis|Kurgan]] immigrants from the region of [[Maikop kurgan|Maikop]] in southern Russia, who spoke an [[Indo-European language]] and perhaps became rulers of the local Hattian population.\u2033<ref>Trevor Bryce, [https://books.google.com/books?id=E1aF0hq1GR8C&pg=PA21 ''The Routledge Handbook of the Peoples and Places of Ancient Western Asia: The Near East from the Early Bronze Age to the Fall of the Persian Empire''.] Routledge, 2013 {{ISBN|1134159080}} p. 21</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHowever, [[Hittitologist]] J.G. Macqueen suggested that these tombs, while constructed by an Indo-European people, were not constructed by [[Anatolian languages|Anatolian]]-speakers, such as Hittites:\n<blockquote>\n\"[...] there is no sign of any spread of this ''kurgan'' culture further south in Anatolia, so it cannot be linked to the spread of Hittite, to say nothing of Palaic or Luwian. The language of the rulers who were buried in the Alaca tombs, although probably Indo-European, was almost certainly not Proto-Hittite.\"<ref>Macqueen, J. G. ''The Hittites, and Their Contemporaries in Asia Minor, revised and enlarged, Ancient Peoples and Places series'', Thames and Hudson, 1996 {{ISBN|0-500-02108-2}} p. 32</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nMany of the [[Hittite Art|artefacts]] discovered at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, including magnificent Hattian gold and bronze objects found in the Royal Tombs, are housed today in the [[Museum of Anatolian Civilizations]] in [[Ankara]]. Among these artefacts are gold and [[electrum]] standing cups and other vessels. The most unusual are the [[Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck bronze standards]]; [[Bull (mythology)|bulls]] or [[Deer (mythology)|stags]] on pedestals whose purpose remains the subject of debate. The standards are cast in copper, many in the form of flat circles, half-circles or squares that are filled with an [[openwork]] network of cross bars, central crosses, and swastikas. [[Leonard Woolley]]<ref>Woolley 1961</ref> found that the Royal Tombs \"seem to belong to the end of a period, as marked by a stratum of destruction and the burning of the citadel. The culture which the tomb objects illustrate does not continue into the next historical phase, that of [[K\u00fcltepe]]\". Modern assessment<ref>Trevor Bryce, ''The Kingdom of the Hittites'' rev. ed., Oxford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-19-928132-7}}</ref> finds that the site continued as a flourishing community to the end of the Late Bronze Age. There was also a sizable occupation in [[Phrygia]]n times.\n\n====Dams====\n\nA [[dam]], dating from 1240 BC, was announced to be reopened for use on September 23, 2006. The dam was ordered by King [[Tudhaliya IV]] in the name of the goddess [[Hebat]]. According to ancient Hittite tablets, a drought struck Anatolia in 1200 BC, prompting the King to import wheat from Egypt so that his land would avoid famine. Following this, the king ordered numerous dams to be built in central Anatolia, all but one of them becoming non-functional over time. The one in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck has survived because the water source is located inside the dam's reservoir.\n\n==Archaeology==\n[[File:Sundisk Alacahoyuk.jpg|A sun disk found in tombs in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck dates back to the early [[Bronze Age]].|thumb|upright]]\nIn 1907, the Ottoman [[archaeology|archaeologist]] [[Theodore Makridi|Theodor Makridi Bey]] carried out brief explorations here for two weeks. \n<ref>Theodor Makrid Bey, La porte des sphinx a Euyuk Fouilles du Musee Imperial Ottoman, Mitteilungen der Vorderasiatisch-Agyp-tischen Gesellschaft, vol. 13, 1908</ref>\nIn the 1910s, [[Germany|German]] teams discovered royal tombs dating to the third millennium BC, as well as a [[Hittites|Hittite]] town of the second millennium BC. The impressive [[sphinx]] gate surrounded by stone reliefs marked its entrance.\n<ref>Robert L. Alexander, A Great Queen on the Sphinx Piers at Alaca H\u00fcy\u00fck, Anatolian Studies, vol. 39, pp. 151-158, 1989</ref> \nThe town was heavily fortified with walls and towers due to the frequent raids of the Kaska people living in the mountainous region to the north.\nExcavations by the [[Turkish people|Turkish]] archaeologists Remzi O\u011fuz Ar\u0131k and [[Hamit Z\u00fcbeyir Ko\u015fay|Hamit Ko\u015fay]] resumed in 1935 under the personal instructions of [[Atat\u00fcrk]] who contributed from his own budget. \n<ref>H. Z. Kosay, Ausgrabungen von Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck: ein Vorbericht \u00fcber die im Auftrage der T\u00fcrkischen Geschichts kommission im Sommer 1936 durchgef\u00fchrten Forschungen und Entdeckungen, TTKY, vol. 2a, 1944</ref><ref>H\u00e2mit Z Kosay and Mahmut Akok, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck excavations : preliminary report on research and discoveries 1963-1967,  \tT\u00fcrk tarih Kurumu yayunlarindan. 5. ser, sa. 28, 1973</ref> The work, which continued until 1970, revealed considerable local wealth and achievement even before the time of the Hittites, with the earliest occupation dating from the 4th millennium BC. Tombs of the 3rd millennium BC feature metal vessels, jewelry, weapons, and pole finials of bulls, stags, as well as abstract forms often interpreted as solar symbols. Excavation at the site resumed in 1994, and is now directed by Dr. Aykut \u00c7\u0131naro\u011flu.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia}}\n*[[Alishar H\u00fcy\u00fck]]\n*[[Cities of the ancient Near East]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Remzi Oguz Arik, Les Fouilles d'Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck: Entreprises par la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'histoire turque. Rapport preliminaire sur les travaux en 1935, Publications de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Turque, 1937\n*Ayse Gursan-Salzmann, Alaca Hoyuk: A reassessment of the excavation and sequence of the Early Bronze Age settlement, University of Pennsylvania, 1992\n*Hamit Z. Ko\u015fay and Mahmut Akok, The Pottery of Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, American Journal of Archaeology, vol. 51, no. 2, pp.&nbsp;152\u2013157, 1947\n*[http://www.noteaccess.com/Texts/Woolley/6.htm  The Art of The Middle East, including Persia, Mesopotamia and Palestine - Woolley]\n*M. J. Mellink, Observations on the Sculptures of Alaca Hoyuk, Anatolia, vol. 14, pp.&nbsp;15\u201327, 1970\n*[https://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/6972/1/uenal_ahmet_6972.pdf] Ahmet Unal, The Textual Illustration of the Jester Scene on the Sculptures of Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, Anatolian Studies, vol. 44, pp.&nbsp;207\u2013218, 1994\n*O.R Gurney, The Ladder-Men at Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, Anatolia Studies, vol. 44, pp.&nbsp;219\u2013220, 1994\n*Piotr Taracha, The Iconographic Program of the Sculptures of Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, Journal of Ancient Near Eastern Religions, vol. 11, iss. 2, pp.&nbsp;132\u2013147, 2011 \n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Euyuk|volume=9|pages=958\u2013959}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck}}\n*[http://ancientneareast.tripod.com/Alaca_Hoyuk.html Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck (ANE)]\n* [http://www.hittitemonuments.com/alacahoyuk/ Images from Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]\n* [http://www.kultur.gov.tr/EN,114132/alacahoyuk.html Republic of Turkey web site for Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]\n* [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/hittite-culture-survives-in-alacahoyuk--44418 \"Hittite culture survives in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck\" - H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]\n\n{{National parks of Turkey}}\n{{Former settlements in Turkey}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alaca Hoyuk}}\n[[Category:\u00c7orum]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites of prehistoric Anatolia]]\n[[Category:Hittite sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Hattian cities]]\n[[Category:Hittite cities]]\n[[Category:National parks of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in the Black Sea Region]]\n[[Category:Geography of \u00c7orum Province]]\n[[Category:History of \u00c7orum Province]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in \u00c7orum Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ancient Hittite site in northern Turkey}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n  |name = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck\n  |native_name = \n  |alternate_name = \n  |image = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 01.jpg\n  |alt = \n  |caption = Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck\n  |map_type = Turkey\n  |map_alt = \n  |map_size= \n  |coordinates = {{coord|40|14|04|N|34|41|44|E|display=inline,title}}\n  |location = [[\u00c7orum Province]], [[Turkey]]\n  |region = [[Anatolia]]\n  |type = Settlement\n  |part_of = \n  |length = \n  |width = \n  |area = \n  |height = \n  |builder = \n  |material = \n  |built = \n  |abandoned = \n  |epochs = \n  |cultures = \n  |dependency_of = \n  |occupants = \n  |event = \n  |excavations = \n  |archaeologists = \n  |condition = In ruins\n  |ownership = \n  |management = \n  |public_access = \n  |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n  |notes = \n}}\n\n'''Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck''' or '''Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck''' (sometimes also spelled as ''Alacah\u00fcy\u00fck'', ''Aladja-Hoyuk'', ''Euyuk'', or ''Evuk'') is the site of a [[Neolithic Age|Neolithic]] and [[Hittites|Hittite]] settlement and is an important [[archaeological site]]. It is situated in [[Alaca]], [[\u00c7orum Province]], [[Turkey]], northeast of [[Bo\u011fazkale]] (formerly and more familiarly [[Bo\u011fazk\u00f6y]]), where the ancient capital city [[Hattusa]] of the [[Hittite Empire]] was situated. Its Hittite name is unknown: connections with [[Arinna]], Tawiniya, and [[Zippalanda]] have all been suggested.<ref>Gorny, Ronald L. \"Zippalanda and Ankuwa: The Geography of Central Anatolia in the Second Millennium B. C.\" ''Journal of the American Oriental Society''. Vol. 117, no. 3, pp. 549-557 (1997).</ref>\n<ref>Popko, Maciej. \"Zippalanda and Ankuwa Once More.\" ''Journal of the American Oriental Society.'' Vol. 120, no. 3, pp. 445-448 (2000).</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sphinx Gate, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 02.jpg|thumb|The Sphinx Gate]]\n\nThe mound ([[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''[[h\u00f6y\u00fck]]'') at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck was a scene of settlement in a continuous sequence of development from the [[Chalcolithic]] Age, when earliest copper tools appeared alongside the use of stone tools.\n\n===Bronze Age===\nDuring the [[Bronze Age|Early Bronze Age]], the mound was the center of a flourishing [[Hattians|Hattian]] culture. It has been continuously occupied ever since, until today's modern settlement in the form of a small village. The standing and distinguishing remains at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, however, such as the \"Sphinx Gate\", date from the [[Hittites|Hittite]] period that followed the Hatti, from the fourteenth century BC.\n\n[[FIle:Royal tomb, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck 02.jpg|thumb|A royal tomb in Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck]]\n\nThirteen [[shaft grave|shaft-grave]] \"Royal Tombs\" (EBII, c. 2350\u20132150 BC) in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck contained the dead in [[fetal position]] facing south. They were richly adorned with gold [[fibula]]e, diadems, and belt buckles and repouss\u00e9 gold-leaf figures.\n\nAccording to [[Trevor Bryce]]:\n<blockquote>\n\u2033There is a theory that the occupants of the tombs were not from the native Hattian population of central Anatolia, but were [[Kurgan hypothesis|Kurgan]] immigrants from the region of [[Maikop kurgan|Maikop]] in southern Russia, who spoke an [[Indo-European language]] and perhaps became rulers of the local Hattian population.\u2033<ref>Trevor Bryce, [https://books.google.com/books?id=E1aF0hq1GR8C&pg=PA21 ''The Routledge Handbook of the Peoples and Places of Ancient Western Asia: The Near East from the Early Bronze Age to the Fall of the Persian Empire''.] Routledge, 2013 {{ISBN|1134159080}} p. 21</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHowever, [[Hittitologist]] J.G. Macqueen suggested that these tombs, while constructed by an Indo-European people, were not constructed by [[Anatolian languages|Anatolian]]-speakers, such as Hittites:\n<blockquote>\n\"[...] there is no sign of any spread of this ''kurgan'' culture further south in Anatolia, so it cannot be linked to the spread of Hittite, to say nothing of Palaic or Luwian. The language of the rulers who were buried in the Alaca tombs, although probably Indo-European, was almost certainly not Proto-Hittite.\"<ref>Macqueen, J. G. ''The Hittites, and Their Contemporaries in Asia Minor, revised and enlarged, Ancient Peoples and Places series'', Thames and Hudson, 1996 {{ISBN|0-500-02108-2}} p. 32</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nMany of the [[Hittite Art|artefacts]] discovered at Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, including magnificent Hattian gold and bronze objects found in the Royal Tombs, are housed today in the [[Museum of Anatolian Civilizations]] in [[Ankara]]. Among these artefacts are gold and [[electrum]] standing cups and other vessels. The most unusual are the [[Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck bronze standards]]; [[Bull (mythology)|bulls]] or [[Deer (mythology)|stags]] on pedestals whose purpose remains the subject of debate. The standards are cast in copper, many in the form of flat circles, half-circles or squares that are filled with an [[openwork]] network of cross bars, central crosses, and swastikas. [[Leonard Woolley]]<ref>Woolley 1961</ref> found that the Royal Tombs \"seem to belong to the end of a period, as marked by a stratum of destruction and the burning of the citadel. The culture which the tomb objects illustrate does not continue into the next historical phase, that of [[K\u00fcltepe]]\". Modern assessment<ref>Trevor Bryce, ''The Kingdom of the Hittites'' rev. ed., Oxford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-19-928132-7}}</ref> finds that the site continued as a flourishing community to the end of the Late Bronze Age. There was also a sizable occupation in [[Phrygia]]n times.\n\n====Dams====\n\nA [[dam]], dating from 1240 BC, was announced to be reopened for use on September 23, 2006. The dam was ordered by King [[Tudhaliya IV]] in the name of the goddess [[Hebat]]. According to ancient Hittite tablets, a drought struck Anatolia in 1200 BC, prompting the King to import wheat from Egypt so that his land would avoid famine. Following this, the king ordered numerous dams to be built in central Anatolia, all but one of them becoming non-functional over time. The one in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck has survived because the water source is located inside the dam's reservoir.\n\n==Archaeology==\n[[File:Sundisk Alacahoyuk.jpg|A sun disk found in tombs in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck dates back to the early [[Bronze Age]].|thumb|upright]]\nIn 1907, the Ottoman [[archaeology|archaeologist]] [[Theodore Makridi|Theodor Makridi Bey]] carried out brief explorations here for two weeks. \n<ref>Theodor Makrid Bey, La porte des sphinx a Euyuk Fouilles du Musee Imperial Ottoman, Mitteilungen der Vorderasiatisch-Agyp-tischen Gesellschaft, vol. 13, 1908</ref>\nIn the 1910s, [[Germany|German]] teams discovered royal tombs dating to the third millennium BC, as well as a [[Hittites|Hittite]] town of the second millennium BC. The impressive [[sphinx]] gate surrounded by stone reliefs marked its entrance.\n<ref>Robert L. Alexander, A Great Queen on the Sphinx Piers at Alaca H\u00fcy\u00fck, Anatolian Studies, vol. 39, pp. 151-158, 1989</ref> \nThe town was heavily fortified with walls and towers due to the frequent raids of the Kaska people living in the mountainous region to the north.\nExcavations by the [[Turkish people|Turkish]] archaeologists Remzi O\u011fuz Ar\u0131k and [[Hamit Z\u00fcbeyir Ko\u015fay|Hamit Ko\u015fay]] resumed in 1935 under the personal instructions of [[Atat\u00fcrk]] who contributed from his own budget. \n<ref>H. Z. Kosay, Ausgrabungen von Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck: ein Vorbericht \u00fcber die im Auftrage der T\u00fcrkischen Geschichts kommission im Sommer 1936 durchgef\u00fchrten Forschungen und Entdeckungen, TTKY, vol. 2a, 1944</ref><ref>H\u00e2mit Z Kosay and Mahmut Akok, Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck excavations : preliminary report on research and discoveries 1963-1967,  \tT\u00fcrk tarih Kurumu yayunlarindan. 5. ser, sa. 28, 1973</ref> The work, which continued until 1970, revealed considerable local wealth and achievement even before the time of the Hittites, with the earliest occupation dating from the 4th millennium BC. Tombs of the 3rd millennium BC feature metal vessels, jewelry, weapons, and pole finials of bulls, stags, as well as abstract forms often interpreted as solar symbols. Excavation at the site resumed in 1994, and is now directed by Dr. Aykut \u00c7\u0131naro\u011flu.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia}}\n*[[Alishar H\u00fcy\u00fck]]\n*[[Cities of the ancient Near East]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Remzi Oguz Arik, Les Fouilles d'Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck: Entreprises par la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'histoire turque. Rapport preliminaire sur les travaux en 1935, Publications de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Turque, 1937\n*Ayse Gursan-Salzmann, Alaca Hoyuk: A reassessment of the excavation and sequence of the Early Bronze Age settlement, University of Pennsylvania, 1992\n*Hamit Z. Ko\u015fay and Mahmut Akok, The Pottery of Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, American Journal of Archaeology, vol. 51, no. 2, pp.&nbsp;152\u2013157, 1947\n*[http://www.noteaccess.com/Texts/Woolley/6.htm  The Art of The Middle East, including Persia, Mesopotamia and Palestine - Woolley]\n*M. J. Mellink, Observations on the Sculptures of Alaca Hoyuk, Anatolia, vol. 14, pp.&nbsp;15\u201327, 1970\n*[https://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/6972/1/uenal_ahmet_6972.pdf] Ahmet Unal, The Textual Illustration of the Jester Scene on the Sculptures of Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, Anatolian Studies, vol. 44, pp.&nbsp;207\u2013218, 1994\n*O.R Gurney, The Ladder-Men at Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck, Anatolia Studies, vol. 44, pp.&nbsp;219\u2013220, 1994\n*Piotr Taracha, The Iconographic Program of the Sculptures of Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck, Journal of Ancient Near Eastern Religions, vol. 11, iss. 2, pp.&nbsp;132\u2013147, 2011 \n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Euyuk|volume=9|pages=958\u2013959}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck}}\n*[http://ancientneareast.tripod.com/Alaca_Hoyuk.html Alaca H\u00f6y\u00fck (ANE)]\n* [http://www.hittitemonuments.com/alacahoyuk/ Images from Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]\n* [http://www.kultur.gov.tr/EN,114132/alacahoyuk.html Republic of Turkey web site for Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]\n* [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/hittite-culture-survives-in-alacahoyuk--44418 \"Hittite culture survives in Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck\" - H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]\n\n{{National parks of Turkey}}\n{{Former settlements in Turkey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alaca Hoyuk}}\n[[Category:\u00c7orum]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites of prehistoric Anatolia]]\n[[Category:Hittite sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Hattian cities]]\n[[Category:Hittite cities]]\n[[Category:National parks of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in the Black Sea Region]]\n[[Category:Geography of \u00c7orum Province]]\n[[Category:History of \u00c7orum Province]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in \u00c7orum Province]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaca_H%C3%B6y%C3%BCk"}
{"title_page": "\u00a1Ay, caramba!", "text_new": "{{short description|Phrase; exclamation used in portugeuse to denote surprise}}\n{{redirect|Caramba}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''\u00a1Ay, caramba!''''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8aj ka\u02c8\u027eamba|pron}}), from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] interjections ''ay'' (denoting surprise or pain) and ''caramba'' (a [[euphemism]] for {{lang|es|[[:wiktionary:carajo|carajo]]}}), is an exclamation used in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] to denote surprise (usually positive).<ref>{{cite book|title=Spanish-English/English-Spanish Dictionary|year=1999|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-345-40547-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780345405470/page/66 66]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780345405470/page/66}}</ref> The term ''caramba'' is also used in Portuguese.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.aulete.com.br/caramba|title=Aulete digital}}</ref> \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" is used as a catchphrase of [[Bart Simpson]] from the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe exclamation became associated with the [[Madrid]] flamenco dancer and singer [[La Caramba]] in the 1780s. Her headdress of brightly colored ribbons became known as a ''caramba''.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZuPJjZLrJHoC&pg=PA26 |title=Spanish Theater Songs -- Baroque and Classical Eras: Medium High Voice |author=Carol Mikkelsen}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xgCQOLBKm28C&pg=PA84 |title=Researching the song |author=[[Shirlee Emmons]], Wilbur Watkin Lewis}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nancy Cartwright.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nancy Cartwright]], the voice of [[Bart Simpson]].]]\n\nThe fictional character [[Bart Simpson]] from the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' (voiced by [[Nancy Cartwright]]) used the phrase \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" (pronounced with an American accent) when surprised. He said it first in the 1988 episode ''The Art Museum''. It became one of his most notable [[catchphrase]]s, further popularizing the phrase in modern [[pop culture]]. For example, in the episode \"[[Selma's Choice]]\", Bart, Lisa, and their Aunt Selma approach a very popular ride at [[Duff Gardens]]. Upon seeing the exceptionally long line for the ride, Bart exclaims, \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Turner |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Turner (author) |title=[[Planet Simpson|Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Defined a Generation]] |others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]. |edition=1st |year=2004 |location=Cambridge |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |oclc=670978714 |isbn=978-0-306-81341-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/planetsimpsonhow00turn_0/page/60 60] }} </ref> \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" were Bart's first words.<ref>S4 E10, \"Lisa's First Words\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[D'oh!]]\n* [[Facepalm]]\n* ''[[Sacrebleu]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{The Simpsons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ay, Caramba}}\n[[Category:Catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Spanish profanity]]\n[[Category:Spanish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons]]\n[[Category:Quotations from television]]\n[[Category:Quotations from animation]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 1988]]\n\n{{Vocab-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Phrase; exclamation used in portugeuse to denote surprise}}\n{{redirect|Caramba}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''\u00a1Ay, caramba!''''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ai ka\u02c8\u027eamba|pron}}), from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] interjections ''ay'' (denoting surprise or pain) and ''caramba'' (a [[euphemism]] for {{lang|es|[[:wiktionary:carajo|carajo]]}}), is an exclamation used in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] to denote surprise (usually positive).<ref>{{cite book|title=Spanish-English/English-Spanish Dictionary|year=1999|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-345-40547-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780345405470/page/66 66]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780345405470/page/66}}</ref> The term ''caramba'' is also used in Portuguese.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.aulete.com.br/caramba|title=Aulete digital}}</ref> \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" is used as a catchphrase of [[Bart Simpson]] from the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe exclamation became associated with the [[Madrid]] flamenco dancer and singer [[La Caramba]] in the 1780s. Her headdress of brightly colored ribbons became known as a ''caramba''.<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZuPJjZLrJHoC&pg=PA26 |title=Spanish Theater Songs -- Baroque and Classical Eras: Medium High Voice |author=Carol Mikkelsen}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xgCQOLBKm28C&pg=PA84 |title=Researching the song |author=[[Shirlee Emmons]], Wilbur Watkin Lewis}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nancy Cartwright.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nancy Cartwright]], the voice of [[Bart Simpson]].]]\n\nThe fictional character [[Bart Simpson]] from the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' (voiced by [[Nancy Cartwright]]) used the phrase \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" (pronounced with an American accent) when surprised. He said it first in the 1988 episode ''The Art Museum''. It became one of his most notable [[catchphrase]]s, further popularizing the phrase in modern [[pop culture]]. For example, in the episode \"[[Selma's Choice]]\", Bart, Lisa, and their Aunt Selma approach a very popular ride at [[Duff Gardens]]. Upon seeing the exceptionally long line for the ride, Bart exclaims, \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Turner |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Turner (author) |title=[[Planet Simpson|Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Defined a Generation]] |others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]. |edition=1st |year=2004 |location=Cambridge |publisher=[[Da Capo Press]] |oclc=670978714 |isbn=978-0-306-81341-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/planetsimpsonhow00turn_0/page/60 60] }} </ref> \"\u00a1Ay, caramba!\" were Bart's first words.<ref>S4 E10, \"Lisa's First Words\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[D'oh!]]\n* [[Facepalm]]\n* ''[[Sacrebleu]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{The Simpsons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ay, Caramba}}\n[[Category:Catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Spanish profanity]]\n[[Category:Spanish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:The Simpsons]]\n[[Category:Quotations from television]]\n[[Category:Quotations from animation]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 1988]]\n\n{{Vocab-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingSpanish IPAperdiscussion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C2%A1Ay,_caramba!"}
{"title_page": "Terms of Service; Didn't Read", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n| name                 = Terms of Service; Didn't Read\n| logo                 = \n| logocaption          = \n| screenshot           = File:ToSDR Ratings.png\n| collapsible          = \n| collapsetext         = \n| caption              = A screenshot showing example ratings from ToS;DR\n| url                  = {{URL|https://tosdr.org/}}\n| commercial           = \n| type                 = \n| registration         = \n| language             = \n| num_users            = \n| content_license      = [[CC BY-SA 3.0]]<ref name=\"legal\">{{cite web|url=http://tosdr.org/legal.html|title=Legal - Terms of Service; Didn&apos;t Read|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n| programming language = \n| owner                = \n| author               = \n| editor               = \n| launch_date          = {{Start date and age|2012|06}}<ref name=\"about page\">{{cite web|url=http://tosdr.org/about.html|title=About - Terms of Service; Didn&apos;t Read|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n| revenue              = \n| alexa                = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady]} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global, MM/YYYY) -->\n| ip                   = \n| current_status       = Active\n| footnotes            = \n}}\n'''Terms of Service; Didn't Read''' ('''ToS;DR''') is a community project which aims to analyze and grade the [[terms of service]] (TOS) and [[privacy policies]] of major Internet sites and services. Each aspect of a TOS or privacy policy is assessed as positive, negative, or neutral. Services are graded from A (best) to E (worst) once a comprehensive list of cases has been reviewed by [[volunteer]] [[curator]]s.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-08/15/tos-dr-website|title=ToS;DR website translates terms of service agreements into English|last=Brown|first=Mark|date=15 August 2012|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=28 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818164016/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-08/15/tos-dr-website|archivedate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Blagdon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/8/14/3241572/tos-dr-terms-of-service|title=ToS;DR reads the terms of service so you don't have to|last=Blagdon|first=Jeff|date=14 August 2012|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Klosowski\">{{cite web|url=http://lifehacker.com/5932853/tosdr-is-a-one-stop-shop-for-webapp-terms-of-service-ratings/all|title=ToS;DR Is a One-Stop Shop for Webapp Terms of Service Ratings|last=Klosowski|first=Thorin|date=8 August 2012|work=[[Lifehacker]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\nThe name of the project is a play on the phrase [[too long; didn't read]].\n\nThe project was founded in June 2012 by Hugo Roy, programmer Michiel de Jong and designer [[Jan-Christoph Borchardt]].<ref>https://tosdr.org/about.html</ref> It was led by Hugo Roy, when he was a law student,<ref name=\"Luckerson\">{{cite web|url=http://business.time.com/2012/08/10/new-site-grades-those-pesky-terms-of-service-agreements-you-never-read/|title=Facebook, Google, Others Have Privacy Policies Explained on New Website|last=Luckerson|first=Victor|date=10 August 2012|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> from 2012 to 2015.\n\n==History==\nSeveral sources of inspiration have been noted for ToS;DR, including [[Creative Commons]]' plain English summaries of licenses, [[European Union energy label|EU energy efficiency ratings]],<ref name=\"Finley\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/08/13/putting-an-end-to-the-biggest-lie-on-the-internet/|title=Putting An End To The Biggest Lie On The Internet|last=Finley|first=Klint|date=13 August 2012|work=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> and [[Aza Raskin]]'s Privacy Icons.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Terms of service]]\n*[[Index of Articles Relating to Terms of Service and Privacy Policies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terms of Service Didn't Read}}\n[[Category:Terms of service]]\n[[Category:Open content projects]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Collaborative projects]]\n[[Category:Contract law]]\n[[Category:Creative Commons-licensed websites]]\n[[Category:Legal websites]]\n[[Category:Firefox add-ons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n| name                 = Terms of Service; Didn't Read\n| logo                 = \n| logocaption          = \n| screenshot           = File:ToSDR Ratings.png\n| collapsible          = \n| collapsetext         = \n| caption              = A screenshot showing example ratings from ToS;DR\n| url                  = {{URL|https://tosdr.org/}}\n| commercial           = \n| type                 = \n| registration         = \n| language             = \n| num_users            = \n| content_license      = [[CC BY-SA 3.0]]<ref name=\"legal\">{{cite web|url=http://tosdr.org/legal.html|title=Legal - Terms of Service; Didn&apos;t Read|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n| programming language = \n| owner                = \n| author               = \n| editor               = \n| launch_date          = {{Start date and age|2012|06}}<ref name=\"about page\">{{cite web|url=http://tosdr.org/about.html|title=About - Terms of Service; Didn&apos;t Read|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n| revenue              = \n| alexa                = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady]} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global, MM/YYYY) -->\n| ip                   = \n| current_status       = Active\n| footnotes            = \n}}\n'''Terms of Service; Didn't Read''' ('''ToS;DR''') is a community project which aims to analyze and grade the [[terms of service]] (TOS) and [[privacy policies]] of major Internet sites and services. Each aspect of a TOS or privacy policy is assessed as positive, negative, or neutral. Services are graded from A (best) to E (worst) once a comprehensive list of cases has been reviewed by [[volunteer]] [[curator]]s.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-08/15/tos-dr-website|title=ToS;DR website translates terms of service agreements into English|last=Brown|first=Mark|date=15 August 2012|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=28 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818164016/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-08/15/tos-dr-website|archivedate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Blagdon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/8/14/3241572/tos-dr-terms-of-service|title=ToS;DR reads the terms of service so you don't have to|last=Blagdon|first=Jeff|date=14 August 2012|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Klosowski\">{{cite web|url=http://lifehacker.com/5932853/tosdr-is-a-one-stop-shop-for-webapp-terms-of-service-ratings/all|title=ToS;DR Is a One-Stop Shop for Webapp Terms of Service Ratings|last=Klosowski|first=Thorin|date=8 August 2012|work=[[Lifehacker]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\nThe name of the project is a play on the phrase [[too long; didn't read]].\n\nThe project was founded in June 2012 by Hugo Roy, programmer Michiel de Jong and designer [[Jan-Christoph Borchardt]].<ref>https://tosdr.org/about.html</ref> It was led by Hugo Roy, when he was a law student,<ref name=\"Luckerson\">{{cite web|url=http://business.time.com/2012/08/10/new-site-grades-those-pesky-terms-of-service-agreements-you-never-read/|title=Facebook, Google, Others Have Privacy Policies Explained on New Website|last=Luckerson|first=Victor|date=10 August 2012|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> from 2012 to 2015.\n\n==History==\nSeveral sources of inspiration have been noted for ToS;DR, including [[Creative Commons]]' plain English summaries of licenses, [[European Union energy label|EU energy efficiency ratings]],<ref name=\"Finley\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/08/13/putting-an-end-to-the-biggest-lie-on-the-internet/|title=Putting An End To The Biggest Lie On The Internet|last=Finley|first=Klint|date=13 August 2012|work=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> and [[Aza Raskin]]'s [http://www.azarask.in/blog/post/privacy-icons/ Privacy Icons].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Terms of service]]\n*[[Index of Articles Relating to Terms of Service and Privacy Policies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terms of Service Didn't Read}}\n[[Category:Terms of service]]\n[[Category:Open content projects]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Collaborative projects]]\n[[Category:Contract law]]\n[[Category:Creative Commons-licensed websites]]\n[[Category:Legal websites]]\n[[Category:Firefox add-ons]]\n", "name_user": "Sebastian Hudak", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:removed external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terms_of_Service;_Didn%27t_Read"}
{"title_page": "The Hollow Men (band)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2010}}\n'''The Hollow Men''' were a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[indie band]] from [[Leeds]], [[England]].  The group named itself after the poem by [[T. S. Eliot]]. The members were David Ashmoore on vocals, Choque on guitar, Howard Taylor on bass, Brian E Roberts on guitar and Jonny Cragg on drums. Between 1985 and 1994 The Hollow Men released four [[album]]s and several [[single (music)|singles]].\n\nStarting out as a two piece for the first single \"Late Flowering Lust\", David Ashmoore (David Owen) and Choque (who was previously in Leeds band Salvation) and session bassist John Dean were joined by permanent bassist Howard Taylor for debut album ''Tales Of The Riverbank'' released on their own Evensong [[record label]].\n\nThe trio recorded another album ''The Man Who Would Be King'' again on Evensong before drummer Jonny Cragg, who had guested on the album and guitarist Brian E. Roberts, a former bandmate of Taylor's when they were in The Passmore Sisters together, joined.\n\nThey signed to [[Arista Records]] in 1988 and released their debut single, \"White Train\", which was a [[remix]]ed version of the song that originally appeared on ''The Man Who Would Be King'' album.  In December 1989, the British music magazine, ''[[NME]]'' reported that The Hollow Men, along with others such as [[Carter the Unstoppable Sex Machine]] and [[The Charlatans (UK band)|The Charlatans]], were their pick as 'stars of tomorrow'.<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 463\n| id= CN 5585}}</ref> The only album the band recorded for Arista was ''Cresta'' released in 1990. The band split up in 1991.\n\nThe album ''Twisted'' made up from unreleased, [[demo (music)|demo]] and live tracks was released in the [[United States|US]] only on November Records in 1994.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Record label\n!valign=\"top\" colspan=\"2\"| '''Chart positions'''\n|-\n\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[UK Albums Chart]]</small>\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[U.S. Pop Albums Chart]]</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1986\n|valign=\"top\"|''Tales Of The Riverbank''\n|align=\"left\"   |Dead Man's Curve \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1988\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[The Man Who Would Be King (album)|The Man Who Would Be King]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |Dead Man's Curve\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1990\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[Cresta (album)|Cresta]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |BMG\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1994\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[Twisted (The Hollow Men album)|Twisted]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |November Records\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n===EPs and singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Record label\n!valign=\"top\" colspan=\"2\"| '''Chart positions'''\n|-\n\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[UK Singles Chart]]</small>\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[Modern Rock Tracks chart|US Modern Rock]]</small>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |1985\n|align=\"left\"   |\"Late Flowering Lust\"\n|align=\"left\"   |Evensong \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|1989\n|align=\"left\"   |\"The Drowning Man\"\n|align=\"left\"   |Blind Eye Records\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |\"White Train\"\n|align=\"left\"   |BMG, Evensong \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"1\"|1990\n|align=\"left\"   |\"The Moon's a Balloon\"\n|align=\"left\"   |Creation\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"|1991\n|align=\"left\"   |\"Live EP\" \n|align=\"left\"   |Arista \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |\"November Comes\"\n|align=\"left\"   |BMG, Evensong, Arista  \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |#16\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |\"Pink Panther\"\n|align=\"left\"   |Evensong \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |\"Pink Panther\"\n|align=\"left\"   |Evensong \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/thehollowmenband/]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hollow Men, The}}\n[[Category:British indie rock groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n'''The Hollow Men''' were a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[indie band]] from [[Leeds]], [[England]].  The group named itself after the poem by [[T. S. Eliot]]. The members were David Ashmoore on vocals, Choque on guitar, Howard Taylor on bass, Brian E Roberts on guitar and Jonny Cragg on drums. Between 1985 and 1994 The Hollow Men released four [[album]]s and several [[single (music)|singles]].\n\nStarting out as a two piece for the first single \"Late Flowering Lust\", David Ashmoore (David Owen) and Choque (who was previously in Leeds band Salvation) and session bassist John Dean were joined by permanent bassist Howard Taylor for debut album ''Tales Of The Riverbank'' released on their own Evensong [[record label]].\n\nThe trio recorded another album ''The Man Who Would Be King'' again on Evensong before drummer Jonny Cragg, who had guested on the album and guitarist Brian E. Roberts, a former band mate of Taylor's when they were in The Passmore Sisters together, joined. \n\nThey signed to [[Arista Records]] in 1988 and released their debut single, \"White Train\", which was a [[remix]]ed version of the song that originally appeared on ''The Man Who Would Be King'' album.  In December 1989, the British music magazine, ''[[NME]]'' reported that The Hollow Men, along with others such as [[Carter the Unstoppable Sex Machine]] and [[The Charlatans (UK band)|The Charlatans]], were their pick as 'stars of tomorrow'.<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 463\n| id= CN 5585}}</ref> The only album the band recorded for Arista was ''Cresta'' released in 1990. The band split up in 1991.\n\nThe album ''Twisted'' made up from unreleased, [[demo (music)|demo]] and live tracks was released in the [[United States|US]] only on November Records in 1994.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Record label\n!valign=\"top\" colspan=\"2\"| '''Chart positions'''\n|-\n\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[UK Albums Chart]]</small>\n!valign=\"top\"| <small>[[U.S. Pop Albums Chart]]</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1986\n|valign=\"top\"|''Tales Of The Riverbank''\n|align=\"left\"   |Dead Man's Curve \n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1988\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[The Man Who Would Be King (album)|The Man Who Would Be King]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |Dead Man's Curve\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1990\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[Cresta (album)|Cresta]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |BMG\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"   |1994\n|valign=\"top\"|''[[Twisted (The Hollow Men album)|Twisted]]''\n|align=\"left\"   |November Records\n|align=\"center\" |\n|align=\"center\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n===EPs and singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!valign=\"top\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!valign